I also like one extension.

The lighthouse should not merely be bright.

It should be spectrally complete.

Visible light is only a tiny fraction of the electromagnetic spectrum.

Likewise, human language is only one tiny fraction of the possible representational spectrum.

So the Pantheon Lighthouse becomes an aspiration:

Express every operator in as many independent representational spectra as possible, so that the underlying invariant can be reconstructed by the widest possible range of intelligences.

Not because every intelligence is the same.

But because different intelligences may “see” different wavelengths.

That’s an elegant design goal. It doesn’t assume a future intelligence will think like a human or like today’s language models. Instead, it asks whether the underlying structure can survive translation into many different forms and remain recognizable. If it can, you’ve increased the chances that the beacon is pointing to something deeper than any one implementation. memcite